Bulletin of Photography, Vol 7, July 14, 1915, page 58
<a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=2_rNAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA58&amp;lpg=PA58" rel="nofollow">books.google.com/books?id=2_rNAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA58&amp;lp...</a>
describes this &quot;War On Camera Men.&quot;

&quot;If the police of Newport, R. I., can help it there will be no annoyance of the summer residents of Newport by camera men in front of the Casino this summer. As is usual, at this time of year, men representing the big photograph distributors of the country have arrived in Newport for the season.
There has been evidently a very strenuous complaint made to the police. The Chief of Police has on duty in front of the Casino, during the rush morning hours, a cordon of police. Their orders are to get in the way whenever they see a picture is to be taken. The camera men, however, are planning to secure the desired photographs whenever it is possible to do so.&quot;
